teresting to note that while Mr.\nl/t-uis is condemned in what one might\ntutm capitalistic circles for his decision\npare down coal stocks, his purpose is\nxt&* r *Uy recognized as a scheme to cut\ndirwn the coal piles in order to strengthen\nthe economic bargaining position of his\nu*on. Production in the mines is out of\nbalance and some miners are working full\ntime while others are out of work.\n\u2022\u2022The mine owners, having an extra 22\nj-Jay* coal supply on the ground, are bar\nw'jtSLning with more spirit this year than\nu*ual. In fact, observers report that the op\nerators show more confidence in their\nVi.*#* talks than they have for years.\nNor do all of the industry\u2019s spokes\nmen seem irritated by the Lewis decision\nto stop soft coal production. In fact, some\n\u25a0'\u25a0\u2014si operators admit that the increasing\nn of coal makes a stoppage wel\nct*me because some of the coal mines have\nrtftf out of ustomers.\nProduction is out of balance but this\nZ \u00b0\u2018ly affects the miners but the sale of\nJ r \"*l t\u00b0 consumers. In other words a large\nnhvMuh above ground weakens the miners\u2019\nbargaining position but it also weakens the\nai** price of coal.\nWE WANT JOBS\n/be number of persons looking for\n)<>i* m May numbered 273,000. The past\nl w **ka showed an increase of employ\nmeat down on the farms amounting to\nr l*.w to 9 million persons. But at present\nti e unemployment is increasing. Somehow\nr another we are all going to get along.\nHome mortgage loans took a nose\ndive during the present year as home loans\nJ have fallen rapidly. There seems to be a\nyrnst deal of bad news about mostly ev-\nI ervthing.\n\nThat is the best government in which\nan injury to one is the concern of all.\u2014\n2 Hulun.\nVV\u2019hat with com on the cob, water\nl melons, peaches and mangoes coming\n\"Vte\u00dff, this life isn\u2019t so bad.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\n\nKey West is playing true touts pole to\nbe the last city in the nation to feel the up\nsurge of prosperity and last to experience\nthe pinch of a recession or depression.\nStories from all' over the nation say\nthat economic belts are tightening, though\nconditiohs are far from those that prevail\nin a depression. It is pretty hard to* deter\nmine the way the economic cat may jump.\nWhile four million persons are linempldy\ned, that number out of 60 million is not\nsufficient to class the economic status as a\ndepression. j\nEconomists admit that we are in the\nmidst of a recession but insist that it mere\nly is a result of the jjoomingf business cor\ning seven or eight years of this decade. in\nKey West, employment has fallen off hjut\nit has not yet reached a stage that may be\ncalled alarming. The Florida State Em\nployment Service in Key West is still find\ning jobs for many applicants, though it\nstill has a waiting list of persons seeking\nemployment.\nHowever, conditions in the nation are\nnot as bad as some Republican senators\nand representatives in Washington would\nhave us believe. In the senate recently,\nsome senators suggested the government\u2019s\nproviding a fund of SSO million to try to\ncounteract the continued increase in un\nemployment, but Democrats asserted that\nit was a political move to try to lead the\npeople of the United States to believe that\nwork is scarer than it really is.\nNaturally, business In Kfey West is\nnot as good as it was during war days, but\nit is holding its own fairly well. The let-up\nin some types of business here is due chief\nly to buyers* resistance, a circumstance\nthat now prevails throughout the nation.\nHonesty is the best insurance policy\nagainst fire in the next world.\nSmear tactics have reached anew\nhigh in ordinary political and publicity\nproceedings.\nTHOROUGH INVESTIGATION\nThe question of national defense is\nbeing investigated by the Armed Services\nCommittee of the House, headed by Rep-\nTesentative Carl Vinson, of Georgia, who\nhas set out an agenda which should be re\nassuring to the people of the United\nStates.\nWhile the inquiry began as a result\nof charges of certain \u201cirregularities\u201d in\nthe Air Force procurement, Mr. Vinson\npoints out that the investigation will go\nmuch further, including a study of the\nbasic assumptions upon which the present\ndefense policies of this country rest.\nFor example, the performance char\nacteristics of the B-36 bomber will be\nlooked into. The missions of the Air Force\nand the Navy, especially in connection\nwith aviation, will be studied. The deci\nsion to cancel the construction of a huge\naircraft carrier will be tested. The wisdom\nof a concentration upon strategic bomb\ning and its relation to tactical aviation and\nthe development of fighter aircraft, will\nbe within the scope of the investigation.\nWe are glad to see that the Congres\nsional committee plans such a comprehen\nsive investigation. Certainly, the matters\nlisted, above should be the subject of in\ntelligent inquiry.\nPity the poor rajahs\u2014reform in vari\nous lands have reduced them to their last\nelephants.\nj\nBASED ON THE ATOM BOMB\nThe defense policy of the United\nStates, it appears, is largely based upon\nthe belief that possession of the atomic\nbomb gives us such a vast superiority over\npotential enemies that another conflict\nwould be no fight.\nDespite this theory, however, Con\ngress is being asked to provide nearly\nsl6, 000,000,000 for national defense. At\nthe same time, the members of Congress,\nunless there are a few execeptions, do not\nknow how many atomic bombs the nation\nhas.\nWith atomic warfare in mind there is\na great urge to place preponderant reli\nance upon the terrific weapon which must\nbe delivered by planes and hence insist\nence upon aircraft as the prime war-power\nof the nation.\nWe have no way of telling whether\nthis is a correct conclusion, or not. Conse\nquently, we think it would b wiser for\nthe people of this country to insist upon\nthe development of more than one type\nof offense and defense. It will cost money\nbut it might be cheaper than losing a war.\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nKEAN FIGHTING ANTI-MASK LAW\n\"ML UHlik.\ngKKgP^k' g*gg||gk RW\nTWO SPOKESMEN In'behalf cf the Ku Klux Klan appear be\nfore the House Committee of the Alabama legislature\nin Montgomery andf protest against a bill to prohibit wearing\nmask in public. The Rev. Alvin Horn (left). Baptist minister\nfrom Talladega. AJfHi acknowledged he is a Klansman. He\ntold the committee the chief purpose of the Klan is to preserve\n\u201cwhite supremacy\".,. I* C. Albright (sight), Birmingham lawyer,\nsaid he is a former member of the Klan. He celled the anti\nmask bill \"a newspaper publicity stunt\" for the \"politicians to\nbid for the Negro vote.\" The committee unanimously approved\nthe bill after the hetuung.\nInteresting Notes\nNew- Hampshire is known as\nthe \u201cGranite State\u201d. f\nThe State motto of lowa is\n\u201cOur Liberties We Prize and Our\nRights We Will Maintain.\u201d\nThe first railroad in America\nwas horse-drawn and was\u2018used in\n1828 to haul granite for the Bunk\ner Hill monument.\ntb greatest thing since water was invented. I\n.w ,h\n1 |-1 rl I I IMI\nJulian Appliance Store\n125 Duval Street Telephone IN\nHaiti means mountainous in the\nnative fondle of that island.\nLEGALS\nSOTtCB\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN that\nthe collector of customs for this\ndistrict has issued a,, ordefr dated\nJune 21, I!MS authorizing the name\nof the gas screw .VIA KM AJO II Of\nficial Number 249552 owned by\nClifton It. Reagan of which Key\nWest, Florida is the home port to\nbe changed to SEA RAIDER 11.\n11. A. WILLIAMS\nCollector\njun2s-27-2S-29,1949\nKey West In\nDays Cone By\nAS TAKEN FROM FILES\nOF THE CFTIZEN OF\nJUNE 27. 1939\ntmitaniitmimimimmHtillHtllllllllllllllltlllllHiniliHl j\nKey West Planning Committee,\nwith Charles Taylor as chairman, i\nmet last night in City Hall and i\ndecided to advocate the adoption\nof a two percent sale s aX ra se\nmoney to match 